- What you got?

13:11.290 --> 13:14.200
We've got some big shards
of pottery here.

13:14.284 --> 13:17.045
And they're all in this area,

13:17.129 --> 13:18.379
- so I didn't want to disturb them too much.
- Perfect.

13:18.464 --> 13:20.590
There's a piece there.

13:22.468 --> 13:25.470
Ooh, and an old bit
of black glass.

13:25.554 --> 13:27.388
It's super bubbly.

13:27.473 --> 13:28.965
So when you find the bubbles,
it means it's older

13:29.049 --> 13:33.135
because the process of
making it was not as refined.

13:33.220 --> 13:37.232
<i>Could archaeologist
Miriam Amirault be correct?</i>

13:37.391 --> 13:41.310
<i>Is this piece of black glass,
found near the stone road,</i>

13:41.395 --> 13:43.813
<i>part of an ancient container?</i>

13:43.897 --> 13:46.816
<i>And if so, will it be
an important clue</i>

13:46.900 --> 13:49.828
<i>to help verify
when the road was constructed?</i>

13:51.405 --> 13:53.081
- Ooh!
- Yep.

13:53.165 --> 13:54.165
GARY:
We've hit the mother lode here!

13:55.501 --> 13:58.244
This will be fun
piecing it together.

13:58.328 --> 14:01.998
Yeah, 1700s written all over it.

14:02.082 --> 14:06.094
You'd have to find
the neck and the rim.

14:06.253 --> 14:07.595
MIRIAM:
Oh, my goodness.

14:07.680 --> 14:11.099
We have not found
this many pieces of,

14:11.183 --> 14:14.769
like, one single artifact
in all of the swamp.

14:14.928 --> 14:16.354
So this is really cool.

14:16.438 --> 14:19.015
- Gorgeous, isn't it?
- That's nice.

14:19.099 --> 14:22.935
This could easily be
an English wine bottle.

14:23.020 --> 14:25.864
We want the finish, the top,

14:25.948 --> 14:28.858
to be definitive about it.

14:28.951 --> 14:31.444
- I mean, it might be here.
- Yep.

14:31.528 --> 14:35.290
- Oh, my gosh.
- What do you have? - Nice!

14:35.374 --> 14:37.500
Is this exactly
what we were looking for?

14:39.870 --> 14:41.212
Yep.

14:41.297 --> 14:43.882
It's a nice finish.

14:43.966 --> 14:46.134
And that's...

14:46.218 --> 14:49.387
1770s, 1780s, I'd say.

14:49.471 --> 14:52.298
Wow. That is so cool.

14:52.382 --> 14:56.802
<i>NARRATOR: An English wine
bottle, dating back as much as</i>

14:56.896 --> 14:59.639
<i>three decades before
the discovery of the Money Pit?</i>

14:59.723 --> 15:03.309
<i>Since the team has found
a number of 18th century British</i>

15:03.393 --> 15:06.571
<i>artifacts across
the island in the past,</i>

15:06.730 --> 15:08.481
<i>could this bottle
have been connected</i>

15:08.565 --> 15:11.242
<i>to a prior searcher
operation on Oak Island?</i>

15:11.327 --> 15:14.820
<i>Or was it left by someone
who made a deposit?</i>

15:14.914 --> 15:19.659
- So I guess this is a good area.
- Yep, top-pocket find.

15:19.743 --> 15:21.077
The more interesting
observation:

15:21.161 --> 15:23.663
look at all these cobbles.

15:23.747 --> 15:27.083
That's stacked rock.
It's about two feet,

15:27.167 --> 15:29.427
maybe two and a half
or three feet tall.

15:29.511 --> 15:30.845
It's very consistent.

15:30.930 --> 15:33.339
That's-that's the aha
right there.

15:33.423 --> 15:35.600
- That's something.
- Yeah.

15:35.684 --> 15:38.678
It's hard to say that that is
not a human intervention.

15:38.771 --> 15:40.104
That's built.

15:40.263 --> 15:42.014
It looks like it's--
The edge of the swamp

15:42.099 --> 15:43.432
was planned, to me,
when I look at this.

15:43.517 --> 15:45.768
But then we got the question:
is this stuff

15:45.852 --> 15:50.365
from this new stone feature
or the stone road?

15:50.449 --> 15:52.367
What's it doing this deep,
down here?

15:52.451 --> 15:53.868
- It's deep, isn't it?
- Yeah, it is.

15:54.027 --> 15:55.703
That's a good question.

15:55.788 --> 15:58.373
<i>NARRATOR:
Another stone structure</i>

15:58.457 --> 16:01.367
<i>at the southeastern
edge of the swamp?</i>

16:01.460 --> 16:04.629
<i>Could it be connected
to the nearby stone wharf,</i>

16:04.713 --> 16:08.457
<i>or is it a completely
different man-made formation?</i>

16:08.542 --> 16:13.388
<i>If so, who built it?
