16:13.472 --> 16:15.131
<i>I'm not really sure
what direction</i>

16:15.215 --> 16:16.224
<i>it's going at this point.</i>

16:16.308 --> 16:18.977
- This is so weird.
- It's fantastic.

16:19.136 --> 16:22.397
I think we need to
try to find the boundary.

16:22.481 --> 16:24.232
<i>There may be a path</i>

16:24.316 --> 16:26.985
that leads south and east
from the stone road.

16:27.069 --> 16:29.895
- Hey, Miriam.
- Hi.

16:29.980 --> 16:32.648
<i>RICK: And so, I think we need
to have Steve Guptill come out,</i>

16:32.733 --> 16:36.485
<i>accurately pin the stones, take
the data, establish boundaries.</i>

16:36.570 --> 16:38.913
Really, I just want
to just survey the update of

16:38.998 --> 16:41.407
- what you guys have uncovered.
- Sure.

16:41.491 --> 16:44.076
<i>NARRATOR: As with the
numerous other man-made features</i>

16:44.169 --> 16:46.078
<i>that the team has discovered
across the island,</i>

16:46.171 --> 16:49.674
<i>professional surveyor
Steve Guptill is recording</i>

16:49.758 --> 16:52.010
<i>the known measurements
and elevation of this feature</i>

16:52.094 --> 16:56.255
<i>so that archaeologists
Miriam Amirault and Laird Niven</i>

16:56.339 --> 16:58.841
<i>can attempt to determine
not only what it may be</i>

16:58.925 --> 17:02.020
<i>but also the purpose
of its construction.</i>

17:02.179 --> 17:04.605
That right there,
I can tell, does tie.

17:04.690 --> 17:06.441
Elevation-wise
and alignment-wise,

17:06.525 --> 17:08.934
- it works with the cobble path.
- Yeah.

17:09.019 --> 17:10.603
Potentially, if it is man-made

17:10.687 --> 17:12.113
and part of some type of path,

17:12.197 --> 17:13.781
it could be an outlet
that heads--

17:13.940 --> 17:15.116
Well, I mean, that's east,

17:15.200 --> 17:16.367
and that's actually towards
the Money Pit.

17:17.953 --> 17:19.704
So, if this is man-made,

17:19.788 --> 17:21.039
this potentially could be
very important.

17:23.042 --> 17:27.286
- Let me survey, and I'm going to put it on a plan when I'm done.
- Okay. Sure.

17:27.370 --> 17:29.622
<i>RICK: It's possible that
this could be part of the path</i>

17:29.706 --> 17:31.632
from the swamp to the Money Pit.

17:31.717 --> 17:33.468
- Right here?
- Yep.

17:33.552 --> 17:35.294
<i>RICK: I mean, it is
an interesting feature.</i>

17:35.387 --> 17:38.389
- Okay?
- And then kind of like right where I am.

17:38.474 --> 17:42.051
<i>RICK: To me, it speaks
to the original paved area.</i>

17:42.135 --> 17:45.137
It does look like that.
It's very well defined.

17:45.222 --> 17:47.482
I'm gonna put this on a plan.

17:47.641 --> 17:49.484
And I'll bring it back so you
can at least take a look at it

17:49.568 --> 17:50.810
- and compare it.
- Yeah.

17:50.894 --> 17:53.154
Yeah, I would project
the stone path line

17:53.238 --> 17:55.564
to see how it interacts
with this.

17:55.657 --> 17:59.660
- Okay.
- And then, just for grins,

17:59.745 --> 18:03.247
- pretend that's a boundary, pretend this is a boundary.
- Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

18:03.332 --> 18:07.409
-Project this line. See where it goes.
-Sure. Yeah.

18:07.494 --> 18:08.753
Just see where it goes.

18:08.837 --> 18:10.329
All right, so I'll see you guys
in a bit.

18:10.413 --> 18:12.423
- Thanks, Steve.
- Thank you.

18:12.508 --> 18:15.093
<i>RICK: It will be interesting
to see what's here.</i>

18:20.006 --> 18:22.842
- Hey, gentlemen.
- Hey, Marty.

18:22.926 --> 18:24.927
I have some
really cool information.

18:25.020 --> 18:26.854
- I really, really do.
- Good news?

18:27.013 --> 18:29.265
I think it's fantastic news.

18:29.349 --> 18:31.016
<i>NARRATOR:
After returning from his trip</i>

18:31.101 --> 18:32.443
<i>to Saint Mary's University</i>

18:32.528 --> 18:35.187
<i>and conducting some
follow-up research on</i>

18:35.280 --> 18:39.450
<i>the partially gold object
retrieved from Borehole D-2,</i>

18:39.609 --> 18:42.111
<i>Marty Lagina has asked
to meet with Rick</i>

18:42.195 --> 18:43.871
<i>and members of the team outside</i>

18:43.956 --> 18:46.040
<i>at the Interpretive Centre.</i>

18:46.125 --> 18:48.450
I met with Dr. Christa Brosseau.

18:48.535 --> 18:51.704
I took a sample from D-2.

18:51.788 --> 18:53.455
- You know, the piece of metal.
- Oh, yeah.

18:53.540 --> 18:56.125
We put it under the electron
microscope and--

18:56.218 --> 18:57.960
By the way, it was
also non-manganese iron.

18:58.053 --> 18:59.971
So it's old iron,
which is also good.

19:00.055 --> 19:01.630
They said, well, let's look
for some bright spots,

19:01.723 --> 19:03.716
- like maybe inclusions.
- Mm-hmm.

19:03.809 --> 19:05.476
Bingo, it's gold.

19:06.970 --> 19:10.064
This is real data.
This is the stuff I like.

19:10.223 --> 19:11.566
And then Dr. Brosseau says,

19:11.650 --> 19:13.809
"Well, if you zoom in
here further

19:13.894 --> 19:15.486
"and do the composition
of the gold,

19:15.645 --> 19:20.408
65% gold, 26% copper,
and five percent silver."

19:20.492 --> 19:23.911
And she says,
"I think that's rose gold."

19:23.996 --> 19:26.906
But if you look up rose gold,

19:26.990 --> 19:30.993
75% gold, 22 and a half
percent copper,

19:31.086 --> 19:34.172
and two and a half
percent silver.

19:34.256 --> 19:36.415
I'm thinking, those
are wildly different numbers.

19:36.508 --> 19:38.009
Yeah.

19:38.093 --> 19:40.928
There's something
called tumbaga gold.

19:41.013 --> 19:42.513
- You ever heard of that, Rick?
- No.

19:42.598 --> 19:44.673
Well, the Aztec,
the Maya and the Inca,

19:44.758 --> 19:47.935
they made their
religious artifacts

19:48.020 --> 19:50.521
out of something called tumbaga,

19:50.680 --> 19:53.265
which was all kinds
of different alloys

19:53.350 --> 19:56.185
of gold, copper and silver.

19:56.269 --> 19:58.270
- That's huge.
- Yeah.

19:58.363 --> 20:02.366
<i>NARRATOR: The partially gold
object recovered from D-2?</i>

20:02.451 --> 20:05.444
<i>Possibly a piece of
Meso-American tumbaga?</i>

20:05.537 --> 20:09.949
<i>Tumbaga was a favored
precious metal alloy mixture</i>

20:10.042 --> 20:12.618
<i>used for creating
jewelry and sacred artifacts</i>

20:12.702 --> 20:16.047
<i>by the indigenous people
of Central and South America</i>

20:16.131 --> 20:18.966
<i>dating back
to as early as 300 AD.</i>

20:19.125 --> 20:22.303
<i>One of the most widely held
theories about the legendary</i>

20:22.462 --> 20:25.881
<i>Oak Island treasure is that
it could be comprised of gold,</i>

20:25.966 --> 20:29.393
<i>silver and jewels that had been
plundered from the New World</i>

20:29.478 --> 20:32.146
<i>between the 16th
and 18th centuries</i>

20:32.305 --> 20:34.398
<i>by Spanish conquistadors.</i>

20:36.059 --> 20:38.653
<i>The Laginas and their
late partner, Dan Blankenship,</i>

20:38.737 --> 20:40.738
<i>have found numerous
Spanish artifacts</i>

20:40.897 --> 20:43.899
<i>across the island
that support this theory,</i>

20:43.984 --> 20:46.235
<i>including ship spikes,</i>

20:46.319 --> 20:48.412
<i>a pair of 17th century scissors,</i>

20:48.571 --> 20:51.499
<i>and even an eight-cob
maravedi coin</i>

20:51.658 --> 20:54.001
<i>dated to 1652.</i>

20:54.086 --> 20:57.913
- Wow.
<i>- However, in 2015,</i>

20:57.998 --> 21:00.332
<i>descendants of Daniel McGinnis,</i>

21:00.417 --> 21:01.917
<i>one of the three young men</i>

21:02.002 --> 21:04.929
<i>who discovered the Money Pit
in 1795,</i>

21:05.088 --> 21:07.756
<i>presented the team
with a gold cross.</i>

21:07.841 --> 21:10.434
<i>A gold cross that McGinnis
reportedly discovered</i>

21:10.593 --> 21:14.188
<i>30 feet deep in
the original treasure shaft.</i>

21:14.347 --> 21:15.940
- We all want answers.
- Okay.

21:16.024 --> 21:17.599
And we're hoping that you can
weigh in on this

21:17.693 --> 21:19.610
- and enlighten us.
- Well, let's see.

21:19.695 --> 21:22.947
<i>NARRATOR: The following year,
the team had the cross examined</i>

21:23.031 --> 21:26.108
<i>by antiquities expert
Dr. Lori Verderame,</i>

21:26.201 --> 21:27.785
<i>and were stunned
by her assessment.</i>

21:27.944 --> 21:30.204
What you have here
is a Christian cross.

21:30.289 --> 21:33.282
In many ways,
it's very Spanish colonial.

21:33.375 --> 21:37.712
The piece dates
between 1550 and 1700.

21:37.796 --> 21:41.540
<i>NARRATOR: Is it possible
that Rick, Marty and the team</i>

21:41.633 --> 21:43.709
<i>have now also recovered
another piece</i>

21:43.802 --> 21:47.796
<i>of Spanish treasure on
Oak Island in Borehole D-2?</i>

21:47.881 --> 21:50.799
<i>And if so, could that mean
that they have finally</i>

21:50.884 --> 21:53.052
<i>located the original Money Pit?</i>

21:53.145 --> 21:57.898
So, we have an odd gold
that happens to fit a narrative

21:57.983 --> 22:00.735
of ancient Spanish gold.

22:02.571 --> 22:04.822
Well, imagine if it was
the same composition.

22:04.906 --> 22:07.900
- Yeah, we'd start to get pretty excited, yeah.
- Yeah.

22:07.984 --> 22:12.330
Corroborative evidence is always
the best measure of whether

22:12.489 --> 22:15.416
or not something is "real,"
quote, unquote.

22:15.500 --> 22:17.576
Great news.
Great science.

22:17.660 --> 22:21.497
But I think one thing
has come of this.

22:21.581 --> 22:22.840
I think, if we were to ask
each other

22:22.924 --> 22:24.416
where are you going to put

22:24.509 --> 22:26.260
at least one of the caissons,
we have a location.

22:26.419 --> 22:27.920
- Yep.
- Yeah.

22:28.004 --> 22:30.348
I think you pretty much have
to put a caisson down there.

22:30.432 --> 22:32.099
We just made our caisson
meeting a little shorter.

22:32.258 --> 22:34.101
- (laughter)
- Well, okay.

22:34.260 --> 22:35.102
- That's great.
- Yep.

22:36.188 --> 22:38.856
Gold in the Money Pit!

22:41.443 --> 22:43.936
<i>NARRATOR:
The following morning...</i>

22:44.029 --> 22:46.864
<i>in the southeast corner
of the Oak Island swamp...</i>

22:47.023 --> 22:47.940
Liz?

22:48.033 --> 22:49.617
- Yeah.
- Give me a hand.

22:49.701 --> 22:53.779
<i>archaeologists Laird Niven,
Miriam Amirault,</i>

22:53.863 --> 22:57.449
<i>and Liz Michels continue
investigating the mysterious</i>

22:57.542 --> 23:01.462
<i>stone feature that was
discovered just one day ago.</i>

23:01.546 --> 23:05.707
- What you got?
- I have a piece of pottery,

23:05.801 --> 23:08.219
but I think it's really
delicate.

23:08.303 --> 23:10.471
So can you make me

23:10.555 --> 23:12.890
a little aluminum foil pouch?

23:13.049 --> 23:14.809
Sure.

23:14.893 --> 23:17.395
I'm just trying to get under it.

23:17.554 --> 23:19.563
- It's pretty deep.
- That's all right, though.

23:19.648 --> 23:21.473
That means it's probably still
in its original context, right?

23:21.566 --> 23:22.483
Exactly. Yeah.

23:24.486 --> 23:28.531
This is where we
find out it's a rock.

23:31.910 --> 23:33.327
You can see it's
definitely pottery, right?

23:33.412 --> 23:34.912
- Yeah.
- But it's really...

23:34.996 --> 23:37.581
- Really degraded.
- really delicate.

23:37.666 --> 23:40.492
- You can see the grit, though.
- Mm-hmm.

23:40.585 --> 23:43.829
Um, and it may have some sort
of decoration on the inside.

23:43.913 --> 23:46.081
You can see it there, but...

23:46.174 --> 23:48.250
I think that has
to go back to the lab.

23:48.343 --> 23:51.095
- Yep.
- Cause it's definitely Mi'kmaq.

23:51.254 --> 23:54.923
This one's the most delicate
I've ever seen.

23:55.016 --> 23:59.687
<i>NARRATOR: Mi'kmaq pottery
discovered along the new stone feature?</i>

23:59.846 --> 24:03.023
<i>As inhabitants of the lands
known today as Nova Scotia,</i>

24:03.183 --> 24:05.267
<i>archaeological evidence suggests</i>

24:05.360 --> 24:07.862
<i>that the indigenous
Mi'kmaq people</i>

24:07.946 --> 24:11.449
<i>have been settled in this
region for at least 4,000 years.</i>

