<i>it is widely documented
that the Mi'kmaq began trading</i>

24:18.123 --> 24:22.209
<i>with European explorers as early
as the late 15th century.</i>

24:22.294 --> 24:27.214
You can see the striations
here, the lines.

24:27.299 --> 24:31.218
We used to call this era
the ceramic period, right?

24:31.377 --> 24:33.721
For the Mi'kmaq. But now
it's called the woodland period.

24:33.880 --> 24:37.382
So this could be 500 years old.

24:37.467 --> 24:39.551
It could be 2,500 years old.

24:39.636 --> 24:42.480
It really depends on what's
revealed on the other side.

24:45.058 --> 24:47.735
<i>I've been expecting, ever
since I've been on Oak Island,</i>

24:47.819 --> 24:50.321
<i>that we would find some
evidence of the Mi'kmaq here.</i>

24:50.480 --> 24:52.156
<i>This evidence
that we're finding right now,</i>

24:52.315 --> 24:55.159
although it's really,
really early days,

24:55.318 --> 24:57.736
<i>and very little area
has been opened,</i>

24:57.829 --> 25:00.739
<i>we need to communicate that
because of</i>

