26:15.148 --> 26:18.492
So, Laird, I'm going to toss it
to you and you can fill them in.

26:18.577 --> 26:22.487
Well, we're finding
Mi'kmaq artifacts,

26:22.581 --> 26:26.408
First Nations artifacts,
in the southeast corner.

26:26.492 --> 26:27.993
Like what items?
What are you finding?

26:28.086 --> 26:29.420
Pottery.

26:29.504 --> 26:30.495
Some Mi'kmaq pottery.

26:30.580 --> 26:31.505
<i>- Oh, really?</i>
- Yeah.

26:31.664 --> 26:33.507
But we did have a visit

26:33.592 --> 26:35.259
from Community,
Culture and Heritage.

26:35.343 --> 26:37.177
- I think it was a very productive visit.
- A positive one.

26:37.262 --> 26:40.005
And they were thrilled
with the find.

26:40.098 --> 26:42.016
And to me it showed
that we're doing our job.

26:42.175 --> 26:43.342
Because it was so careful,

26:43.435 --> 26:46.678
we were able to basically
not disturb anything.

26:46.763 --> 26:49.690
So they were thrilled with that.

26:49.849 --> 26:52.684
But one thing they need to do is
get a hold of Acadia First Nation

26:52.769 --> 26:54.361
and see if they're interested

26:54.446 --> 26:58.774
in coming to the island
for a site visit.

26:58.858 --> 27:00.451
<i>CRAIG:
I think that's a great idea.</i>

27:00.610 --> 27:02.453
Let's do it. I don't have
a problem with that.

27:02.537 --> 27:04.946
But Laird has brought up
a concern,

27:05.031 --> 27:06.874
- and I think it needs to be addressed.
- Okay.

27:06.958 --> 27:09.043
LAIRD: Because of
the Mi'kmaq artifacts,

27:09.127 --> 27:10.369
Community, Culture and Heritage

27:10.462 --> 27:11.629
may require us

27:11.788 --> 27:14.048
- to stop work in that area.
- Okay.

27:16.959 --> 27:18.543
<i>NARRATOR:
Although finding artifacts</i>

27:18.637 --> 27:20.629
<i>that may date back
more than 20 centuries</i>

27:20.722 --> 27:23.057
<i>on Oak Island is exciting,</i>

27:23.216 --> 27:27.469
<i>their potential connection to
the Mi'kmaq people could result</i>

27:27.562 --> 27:30.972
<i>in the provincial Department of
Community, Culture and Heritage</i>

27:31.057 --> 27:33.984
<i>and the Acadia
First Nation Mi'kmaq Council</i>

27:34.069 --> 27:37.229
<i>declaring the eastern portion
of the swamp off-limits</i>

27:37.313 --> 27:39.490
<i>for further search activity.</i>

27:39.574 --> 27:42.493
We're trying to find a way
to work within the constraints

27:42.577 --> 27:46.071
- of CCH...
- Mm-hmm.

27:46.164 --> 27:47.498
To find a way to move forward
on all fronts.

27:47.582 --> 27:49.908
We've been doing
everything right.

27:50.001 --> 27:54.004
I'm hopeful that all sides
will enter into a very fruitful

27:54.089 --> 27:57.332
and honest discussion
about how we can mitigate.

27:57.425 --> 27:58.500
<i>MARTY:
Yeah, I agree.</i>

27:58.593 --> 28:00.168
<i>Are we going to cooperate?</i>

28:00.253 --> 28:02.429
<i>Hell yes. Are we going
to do it right? Yes.</i>

28:02.514 --> 28:04.256
<i>Are we going to follow
the rules? Yes.</i>

28:04.349 --> 28:07.008
Because we have found
First Nation artifacts

28:07.093 --> 28:09.103
here on Oak Island,
we have a duty to notify

28:09.262 --> 28:12.097
both CCH and First Nation.

28:12.181 --> 28:15.609
<i>Am I worried about what they
might say or do or require?</i>

28:15.694 --> 28:17.695
<i>Yeah, I'm concerned,
because, look,</i>

28:17.854 --> 28:20.021
<i>it's yet another level
of supervision.</i>

28:20.106 --> 28:21.949
<i>But does that dissuade me
from doing it?</i>

28:22.033 --> 28:24.276
<i>No, it's the right thing to do.</i>

28:24.360 --> 28:26.528
They have certain rights
under Nova Scotia law.

28:26.612 --> 28:28.038
We're gonna abide by that.

28:28.197 --> 28:30.290
RICK:
The overarching realization

28:30.375 --> 28:33.377
has to be that,
without the mystery,

28:33.461 --> 28:36.538
nothing else goes on.

28:36.622 --> 28:38.882
Without you trying to solve
the mystery,

28:38.967 --> 28:41.042
nothing else goes on.

28:41.136 --> 28:43.712
<i>RICK:
CCH is well-intentioned,</i>

28:43.796 --> 28:47.641
but they have said--
And I hope we hold them to it--

28:47.800 --> 28:50.051
That they will work with us.

28:50.136 --> 28:53.638
<i>Well, you know, look,
appreciate the update.</i>

28:53.723 --> 28:55.899
<i>I guess Laird will do his thing
over there in the southeast</i>

28:55.984 --> 28:57.818
<i>until he's satisfied</i>

28:57.977 --> 29:01.646
and CCH is satisfied, and
we'll... we'll go dig elsewhere.

29:01.740 --> 29:03.907
-Oh, yeah.
-I agree. We have to take advantage

29:04.066 --> 29:05.901
of what we can do
in the near term.

29:05.985 --> 29:08.245
<i>Okay, well, carry on.</i>

29:08.404 --> 29:10.831
- All right.
- Okey doke. Hopefully we'll have

29:10.915 --> 29:12.833
another update for you
that's a bit more positive.

29:12.992 --> 29:14.418
(Rick chuckles)

29:14.502 --> 29:15.919
<i>Okay, Rick. Thanks.</i>

29:16.004 --> 29:17.913
<i>- RICK: See you, guys.
- MARTY: Yeah. Bye-bye.</i>

29:17.997 --> 29:21.249
<i>NARRATOR:
Later that afternoon...</i>

29:21.334 --> 29:23.677
<i>while the core-drilling
operation continues</i>

29:23.836 --> 29:25.179
<i>in the Money Pit area...</i>

29:29.100 --> 29:31.843
<i>STEVE G.: Rick asked me to survey
the patch that we're standing on.</i>

29:31.928 --> 29:33.261
I do have that image now.

29:33.346 --> 29:35.931
When you projected
the two things that I asked you

29:36.024 --> 29:38.275
- to project, was there any aha moments?
- Yeah. Yeah, actually.

29:38.359 --> 29:40.444
We'll talk about that.

29:40.603 --> 29:42.696
<i>NARRATOR:
Rick Lagina and Laird Niven</i>

29:42.781 --> 29:45.023
<i>head back to the southeast
corner of the swamp</i>

29:45.107 --> 29:47.284
<i>with other members of the team.</i>

29:47.443 --> 29:50.028
I don't have an opinion.
I have facts.

29:50.112 --> 29:51.696
<i>NARRATOR: They have
gathered to receive a report</i>

29:51.781 --> 29:53.540
<i>from surveyor Steve Guptill</i>

29:53.699 --> 29:56.960
<i>regarding the stone feature
discovered one day ago</i>

29:57.119 --> 29:59.871
<i>and the direction
it may be heading.</i>

29:59.956 --> 30:02.958
Here is an overview of the area.

30:03.042 --> 30:04.218
And here is a projection
of the current path

30:04.377 --> 30:06.553
we're standing on.

30:06.638 --> 30:08.463
So this is the cobble path
from last year.

30:08.548 --> 30:10.382
It hits the cobble
that we found this year,

30:10.466 --> 30:11.725
which is what we're standing on.

30:11.884 --> 30:13.227
The elevation is very close.

30:13.311 --> 30:15.896
Now, that is
one foot, eight inches.

30:15.980 --> 30:18.315
Where it joins here,
this is it here.

30:18.399 --> 30:19.983
This is a larger overview.

30:20.142 --> 30:22.143
Rick asked me
to project the line

30:22.237 --> 30:24.062
on the north and south side.

30:24.155 --> 30:28.659
I projected this cobble path
across the lots.

30:28.743 --> 30:30.986
And so, when you project this
path, it heads to the Money Pit.

30:31.079 --> 30:33.330
- This path?
- This path here.

30:37.502 --> 30:38.493
Look right here.

30:38.586 --> 30:40.245
There's the Money Pit grid.

30:40.329 --> 30:41.746
- Yep.
- C-1 is right there.

30:41.840 --> 30:44.341
It projects just north
of C-1 a couple feet.

30:44.425 --> 30:45.926
That's interesting.

30:46.085 --> 30:48.253
IAN:
It makes some sense,

30:48.346 --> 30:50.180
because we're going
into the upland here.

30:50.265 --> 30:51.765
- Yeah.
- This is it.

30:51.850 --> 30:53.258
This is what
we've been looking for.

30:53.342 --> 30:55.686
Right.

30:55.845 --> 30:59.606
<i>NARRATOR: Has the team now
unearthed a previously hidden section</i>

30:59.765 --> 31:01.516
<i>of the stone pathway?</i>

31:01.601 --> 31:04.102
<i>One that leads directly
from the stone wharf</i>

31:04.195 --> 31:07.364
<i>to the C-1 cluster
in the Money Pit area?</i>

31:07.448 --> 31:10.025
<i>The same area where they
have not only found evidence</i>

31:10.109 --> 31:13.028
<i>of silver and gold
deep below ground,</i>

31:13.112 --> 31:15.372
<i>but also where they
are currently drilling</i>

31:15.531 --> 31:18.208
<i>in search
of the legendary treasure vault?</i>

31:18.293 --> 31:23.463
<i>If so, what other valuable clues
might they discover here?</i>

31:23.548 --> 31:25.540
<i>RICK: I don't know that
any of us were expecting</i>

31:25.633 --> 31:27.459
<i>what we'll call
the "stone path."</i>

31:27.543 --> 31:30.804
<i>But let's expand the search area</i>

31:30.963 --> 31:33.724
and try to find out, you know,
additional information.

31:33.808 --> 31:35.383
IAN: I think something really
important's being found here.

31:35.468 --> 31:37.552
They were going this way.

31:37.645 --> 31:40.472
- And why go this way if you're a fisherman or a farmer?
- RICK: Right.

31:40.556 --> 31:44.067
- Okay. Well, let's try to understand this feature.
- Absolutely.

31:48.397 --> 31:50.982
<i>NARRATOR: As another
day begins on Oak Island,</i>

31:51.067 --> 31:54.661
<i>and while the excavation of
the possible stone path feature</i>

31:54.746 --> 31:58.081
<i>in the southeast corner
of the swamp continues...</i>

31:58.166 --> 32:00.500
<i>CRAIG:
Okay, we got our sample coming.</i>

32:00.585 --> 32:02.160
<i>NARRATOR:
in the Money Pit area,</i>

32:02.253 --> 32:04.245
<i>Craig Tester</i>

32:04.330 --> 32:06.089
<i>and geologist Terry Matheson...</i>

32:08.009 --> 32:10.761
<i>continue to oversee
the core-drilling operation</i>

32:10.920 --> 32:13.672
<i>in the C-1 cluster
at Borehole B-4...</i>

32:13.756 --> 32:16.007
Eighty-nine?

32:16.092 --> 32:18.343
<i>a borehole that they hope</i>

32:18.427 --> 32:20.437
<i>will eventually encounter
more evidence</i>

32:20.521 --> 32:22.514
<i>of the legendary Chappell Vault</i>

32:22.598 --> 32:26.360
<i>at a depth
of approximately 150 feet.</i>

32:26.519 --> 32:30.105
- 89.
- 89. Thank you.

32:30.189 --> 32:32.866
83 to 89.

32:32.951 --> 32:34.284
Here in front of us.
What do we got?

32:34.443 --> 32:36.703
STEVE G.:
Anything going on down there?

32:36.788 --> 32:38.863
- Yeah.
- Yeah?

32:38.948 --> 32:41.458
CRAIG: Yeah. A little bit
of wood at the very bottom.

32:41.542 --> 32:44.044
(chuckles):
Look at that. Wow.

32:44.128 --> 32:46.546
<i>NARRATOR:
Wood? Found at a depth</i>

32:46.631 --> 32:50.291
<i>of nearly 90 feet
in Borehole B-4?</i>

32:50.376 --> 32:52.794
-TERRY: Okay, We got disturbed
material, -Right on the edge there.

32:52.878 --> 32:55.973
- Yeah.
- We're close to our tunnel horizon.

32:56.057 --> 32:57.808
We hit it 88 to 92.

32:57.892 --> 32:59.968
So we're
right in the sweet spot here.

33:00.052 --> 33:02.229
Looks like we got something
very interesting.

33:02.313 --> 33:06.141
<i>NARRATOR: Although they were
hoping to reach a structure much deeper,</i>

33:06.225 --> 33:09.310
<i>it was at a depth
of some 90 feet where,</i>

33:09.395 --> 33:12.564
<i>one week ago, the team
obtained not only wood,</i>

33:12.648 --> 33:17.318
<i>but also the gold object
from Borehole D-2.</i>

33:17.403 --> 33:21.573
<i>Is it possible that they've just
encountered the same structure?</i>

33:21.666 --> 33:23.491
<i>And, if so,</i>

33:23.576 --> 33:25.669
<i>could it also be connected
to the evidence</i>

33:25.828 --> 33:28.413
<i>of a massive source
of gold and silver</i>

33:28.506 --> 33:31.591
<i>recently detected
through water sample testing?</i>

33:31.676 --> 33:35.262
We have somebody shaping wood
to make a tunnel or a shaft.

33:35.346 --> 33:38.673
The next drill intersection
will tell the tale, hopefully.

33:38.758 --> 33:40.267
The core drill is
coming out of the ground now.

33:40.351 --> 33:42.102
- CHARLES: Here we go.
- Here we go.

33:42.261 --> 33:44.679
<i>RICK: Every time the drill goes
down now versus other years,</i>

33:44.764 --> 33:46.356
<i>the hope is to slice open</i>

33:46.441 --> 33:49.609
the plastic, and voilà,
there's gold, there's silver.

33:49.694 --> 33:52.353
Part of a chest.
Part of something.

33:52.447 --> 33:54.439
A definite.
Maybe even the one,

33:54.523 --> 33:57.692
my long sought after,
elusive one thing.

33:57.777 --> 33:59.119
<i>There is something down there.</i>

33:59.203 --> 34:01.863
Core intersection,

34:01.956 --> 34:03.373
- we'll see what it tells us.
- 93.

34:03.458 --> 34:06.043
- 93?
- Thank you.

34:08.954 --> 34:10.714
All right.

34:12.041 --> 34:15.210
- Oh! I can see goodness.
- Yep.

34:15.303 --> 34:17.378
- You see something?
- I can see

34:17.463 --> 34:20.223
definitely something of interest
right about there.

34:20.308 --> 34:22.467
- Okay, whoa, look at that, gentlemen.
- There we go.

34:22.551 --> 34:23.968
That looks like we went right
through the floor of a tunnel.

34:24.053 --> 34:26.721
That is definitely sawn wood,

34:26.806 --> 34:30.975
and it looks like
a relatively irregular handsaw.

34:31.060 --> 34:33.311
Craig, what do you think?

34:33.395 --> 34:35.405
Yeah, I'm with you.

34:35.490 --> 34:38.399
This part, the blades are coming
at a little different angle.

34:38.484 --> 34:40.902
Yeah. That says
somebody's heaving and pulling.

34:40.986 --> 34:42.487
Yep.

34:42.571 --> 34:44.414
STEVE G.:
So, based on what we see,

34:44.573 --> 34:47.250
would you call this a shaft
or a tunnel?

34:47.335 --> 34:50.754
That could well be
the floor planks

34:50.838 --> 34:52.923
of a tunnel, definitely.

34:53.007 --> 34:56.176
TERRY: We've got a
very, very interesting area

34:56.260 --> 34:58.336
in and around C-1.

34:58.429 --> 35:01.431
STEVE G.: It almost
seems like we can't miss.

35:04.844 --> 35:07.687
<i>NARRATOR:
Later that afternoon,</i>

35:07.772 --> 35:09.848
<i>after being alerted
by Laird Niven</i>

35:09.932 --> 35:11.525
<i>of an update from the Department</i>

35:11.609 --> 35:13.184
<i>of Community,
Culture and Heritage...</i>

35:13.269 --> 35:15.270
- Hey, Rick.
- Hey, Rick.

35:15.354 --> 35:18.115
<i>Rick Lagina has called
an emergency meeting</i>

35:18.199 --> 35:21.025
<i>with his brother Marty,
their partner Craig Tester,</i>

35:21.110 --> 35:24.445
<i>and members of the team
in the war room.</i>

35:24.530 --> 35:26.623
RICK:
We have everybody here

35:26.707 --> 35:29.042
that could come out of the field
in the war room right now.

35:29.127 --> 35:31.202
And you know what the discussion
is related to:

35:31.287 --> 35:33.454
the archaeological work

35:33.539 --> 35:36.716
and the fallout, if you will,
from notifying

35:36.876 --> 35:38.552
the Acadia First Nations.

35:38.636 --> 35:41.972
And I wanted everyone
to understand

35:42.056 --> 35:43.882
the current situation.

35:43.975 --> 35:45.892
So, Laird, if you want
to bring everyone up to speed.

35:45.977 --> 35:49.053
Well, basically,
Acadia First Nation

35:49.138 --> 35:51.481
got hold of Community,
Culture and Heritage.

35:51.566 --> 35:53.900
<i>MARTY:
Okay.</i>

35:53.985 --> 35:55.977
And before you go
any further, Laird,

35:56.061 --> 35:58.488
<i>it's the pottery
that's causing the concern?</i>

35:58.573 --> 36:00.732
Presumably so, yeah.

36:00.816 --> 36:02.817
The pottery we found

36:02.902 --> 36:05.579
mean that they were there
for some period of time.

36:05.663 --> 36:07.822
How long they were there,
we don't know.

36:07.907 --> 36:10.584
They have requested maps
and all the information

36:10.668 --> 36:13.244
and all the data
as regards the finds,

36:13.329 --> 36:16.080
the locations, the depths,
the elevations.

36:16.165 --> 36:18.758
Steve is working on that,
and I have some suspicion

36:18.843 --> 36:21.502
and belief that
they won't respond

36:21.596 --> 36:23.513
until that information is
in hand.

36:23.672 --> 36:24.923
Yeah.

36:25.007 --> 36:27.267
And the archaeologists asked

36:27.351 --> 36:28.810
that we stop down.

36:30.846 --> 36:35.108
Stop work at the area where
we're finding the artifacts.

36:35.193 --> 36:37.694
It's just a blanket prohibition,

36:37.778 --> 36:40.030
because they
haven't been here yet.

36:41.199 --> 36:42.699
I see.

36:42.858 --> 36:45.368
I.e. "you must cease."
And those were...

36:45.453 --> 36:46.870
that was the verbiage:
"you must cease

36:46.954 --> 36:49.197
and desist immediately."

36:49.281 --> 36:51.041
Well...

36:59.884 --> 37:02.052
Honestly, I'm becoming

37:02.136 --> 37:02.961
increasingly more frustrated
with this whole thing.

37:03.045 --> 37:04.387
<i>NARRATOR:
In the war room,</i>

37:04.472 --> 37:07.807
<i>Rick Lagina
and archaeologist Laird Niven</i>

37:07.892 --> 37:10.310
<i>have just informed
the Oak Island team that</i>

37:10.469 --> 37:12.553
<i>the provincial Department of
Community, Culture and Heritage</i>

37:12.638 --> 37:15.065
<i>are restricting search activity</i>

37:15.224 --> 37:17.150
<i>in the southeast corner
of the swamp,</i>

37:17.309 --> 37:19.319
<i>after the team unearthed</i>

37:19.403 --> 37:22.155
<i>indigenous Mi'kmaq artifacts
there.</i>

37:22.240 --> 37:24.565
RICK: I think
what we're trying to do

37:24.650 --> 37:28.236
is understand exactly
what the prohibitions are.

37:28.320 --> 37:29.579
- Correct?
- Yeah.

37:29.664 --> 37:31.322
STEVE G.:
Let me show you some areas.

37:31.407 --> 37:33.416
I'll share my screen, Marty.

37:35.160 --> 37:38.746
<i>MARTY: What is the big green and
big red polygon to the right?</i>

37:38.831 --> 37:41.508
<i>- What are those?</i>
- So, this is for drilling.

37:41.592 --> 37:44.094
<i>We have free range
inside of the green.</i>

37:44.178 --> 37:47.013
Any activity inside the green,
we're allowed to pursue.

37:47.098 --> 37:48.014
I see.

37:48.099 --> 37:50.016
<i>And the red?</i>

37:50.101 --> 37:52.018
Anything that falls
outside of the green,

37:52.103 --> 37:55.772
we need special permission
to be inside of the red.

37:59.110 --> 38:00.435
The problem is,

38:00.519 --> 38:03.021
the area we're digging
seems to indicate

38:03.105 --> 38:06.032
where the stone road and the
associated stone path was going.

38:06.117 --> 38:08.776
Appears to be going
to the upland.

38:08.861 --> 38:11.446
Appears to be going to...
towards the Money Pit.

38:11.530 --> 38:13.707
<i>MARTY:
We need to go dig over there.</i>

38:13.866 --> 38:15.283
<i>Guess what. We can't.</i>

38:15.367 --> 38:17.201
Just look at that map
that's in front of us.

38:17.295 --> 38:20.880
"See this green area?
Okay, guys, that can be yours.

38:20.965 --> 38:24.551
The rest is kind of ours."
Look at the map.

38:24.635 --> 38:26.720
(laughs):
It's... I mean, come on.

38:26.804 --> 38:27.887
<i>BILLY:
I'm with you, Marty.</i>

38:27.972 --> 38:29.639
And I know Oak Island is
a special place.

38:29.724 --> 38:31.049
I get that, right?

38:31.133 --> 38:32.642
But everything
that's been done--

38:32.727 --> 38:34.728
And I'm with Marty on this one--
Everything that's been done

38:34.812 --> 38:37.480
to this point,
there's far more oversight here.

38:37.565 --> 38:38.815
I can go across the island

38:38.899 --> 38:40.558
and dig all the holes
that I want to,

38:40.642 --> 38:41.735
and nobody's gonna stop me.

38:41.819 --> 38:43.486
It seems unfair
and it seems ridiculous.

38:43.571 --> 38:45.739
<i>Billy, that's
completely correct.</i>

